Isn't there a need to call end session at the time of disconnect?

Though this should work, this should be done efficiently to avoid many process hops between driver and server.  It would be better to send a message to the server and encapsulate this logic in the server.
It would be good to add some summary info about JIRA in the same line as the [TRAFODION-1986]. Otherwise it just shows an empty subject.

@selvaganesang: Just wanted to ask, what's the follow-on action? Should we commit this change, and also write another JIRA to improve the efficiency? Another question I wanted to ask, just for my own education: How many process hops does this have? I see one where we execute the statement. Do the properties changes also imply process hops?

Hi Selva,
On abort transaction if we get an unknown transaction exception I think we need to decrement the request pending count.  We sent the message and got a reply in the form of an exception, so we are not waiting on an additional reply, but if the count never gets to zero we’ll hang.

Regards,
Sean

On further discussion with Narendra, it is found that 

Trafodion.dtm.log shows that the transaction abort returned unknownTransaction from RS

2016-07-29 08:25:07,561 ERROR transactional.TransactionManager: Abort of transaction: 94547 participantNum: 2 region: TRAFODION.S025.T025T005,,1469780693295.8b5acee4643097d33435d2250e6a7d3b. threw Exception: java.io.IOException: UnknownTransactionException

This UnknownTransactionException is the DoNotRetryIOException. It looks like this exception may not be completing the request and hence it is possible that we are hung. 

I am retaining my workspace in this state so that we can debug further if we need to.

Selva

@selvaganesang : Moving the setting logic to server side is an good idea, and the way of doing so is using SetConnectionOption() method to send the message. However, the problem is we don't have data source management now, so driver is not 100% aware of the current catalog the session is on, especially if a "set catalog" was executed during the session lifetime. So if we want to set the schema via SetConnectionOption() method, we must call getCatalog() to retrieve the catalog name from server first, otherwise server will always use the default catalog name to concatenate with the schema name. thus it won't do any help for improving the efficiency. This is the only choice we have right now.
